I strongly disagree with you there.  First the last real Indy 500 ran
in May of 1995.  The IRL 500 has never shown any growth with the
possible exception of purse (and that would have to be adjusted for
inflation) but everything else is way way down for the IRL 500.  Is it
still a money maker?  For now, but not nearly as much as it once was.
Maybe its paying the bills for the rest of the year, but I doubt it.
The Brickyard maybe filling the gap, but it doesn't matter.

The Hulman Company, the real income source makes a number of products
including Clabber Girl Baking Powder.  Tony has the resources to put a
field of 33 cars in place for the IRL 500 for the rest of his life
should he choose to do so with not a cent from anything other than the
other businesses.  The way open wheel racing is going he might be
looking at a bill for fielding all 33 cars at the IRL 500 in the not
too distant future.

All he had to do was nothing, and open wheel would have far far better
off.  He couldn't even seem to do nothing right.

Over the long term, Champ Car has a better shot than most realize
going international.  It just doesn't include me.  In time it could
once again challenge F1 if F1 can't get itself together.  With the
loss of the Indy 500, the spec IRL 500 just hasn't had the life
support turned off.  Ego can be a powerful thing.  I doubt it will
anytime soon, but I could see any of several events happening that
could trigger events that could put the IRL 500 at risk.
