The Indianapolis Star a couple of years ago had a reporter walk and
count every seat at IMS and came up with a number of around 260,000.
It has been reported many times that IMS has never sought tax
abatement or any direct government subsidy (unlike our Colts) so if
they are getting any tax breaks, I would argue they are getting the
same ones open to any business under the tax codes. Clearly open wheel
is suffering and I doubt anyone would say it's in better shape now
than in 95 before the split, but I saw more empty seats at the
Brickyard this year than at the 500 for the first time. I think racing
in all forms is hurting as the economy limps along, jobs are
disappearing overseas and foreclosures are at an all-time high. So TG
is an easy target for all that ails top level US open wheel racing,
but the bottom line IMO is that nothing will change until unification
occurs, and maybe not even then. The casual fan doesn't know the dif
between a Dallara, Panoz or a Williams, and until they start going to
the track for the racing (not the hype ala WWSprintcup) open wheel is
arguably reduced to a niche sport with diehard fans like the people on
this forum who are passionate about it and willing to spend time and
money to support their favorite series. It's all good, whatever series
you support, but please let's get them together before the diehards
like us die off.
